[normal]PHE’s Knowledge and Intelligence Service[bold]&#xa0;[bold]On 1 April 2013 the regi
[normal]onal Public Health Observatories (PHOs) transferred along with the specialist observatories and the National Cancer Intelligence Network into PHE as a single Knowledge and Intelligence service for England.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The historical role of the PHOs remains fundament
[normal]ally unchanged and is now carried out by PHE’s eight Knowledge and Intelligence Teams.  We are building on the highly regarded work of our predecessor organisations to ensure we have a knowledge service to ensure decisions we make about health are based on
[normal] the best information and evidence available and allow us to secure the best possible
[normal] outcome.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]PHE continues to produce a range of interactive resources, reports and profiling tools to help local government and the health service understand health need, make comparisons with other areas and make informed 
[normal]d
[normal]ecisions.  A flavour of our work is given by
[normal] the brief description of some of our key products set out in Annex A.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]All of our resources remain accessible on-line through PHE’s website: (
[normal]www.gov
[normal].
[normal]uk/
[normal]P
[normal]HE
[normal]) and our data and knowledge portal (
[normal]www.datagat
[normal]e
[normal]way.phe.org.uk
[normal]) which allows access to resources across the 140 legacy sites that previously supported the full range of our products.  All legacy sites will be migrated to a new single site.  We are currently working 
[normal]with our users to identify their needs and with the Government Digital Service on the design of the new site. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]PHE will work closely with 
[normal]t
[normal]he National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) to ensure access to high quality public health evidence
[normal] and advice.  NICE is responsible for setting quality standards for health, social care and public health. PHE will ensure full integration of evidence resources from the NICE evidence service into t
[normal]he PHE Knowledge service.  Our K
[normal]nowledge service will als
[normal]o include evidence and guidance from other sources such as the National Screening Committee and 
[normal]the 
[normal]Joint Committee on Vaccination and immunisation.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]If any members of the Committee have any queries about the Knowledge and Intelligence Service, our 
[normal]products, or information needs
[normal],
[normal] please contact our Chief Knowledge Officer, Professor John Newton (
[normal]john.newton@phe.gov.uk
[normal]) who would be delighted to help.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]The Evidence on the impact of Minimum Unit Pricing[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Th
[normal]ere is strong evidence
[normal] to support alcohol Minimum Unit Pricing (MUP) as an effective strategy to reduce alcohol consumption and alcohol related harms.  The largest impacts would be experienced by hazardous drinkers with somewhat smaller impacts on moderate
[normal] drinkers.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The latest modelling work by the experts at the University of Sheffield, published in July this year, looks at the impact on consumption and alcohol related harms of a minimum unit price of 40p, 45p and 50p.  Their key findings are set out in t
[normal]he table below, and their full report can be found at 
[normal](he
[normal]r
[normal]e)
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
