[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Other countries have introduced minimum pricing policies for alcohol and their experience provides empirical evidence of 
[normal]the impact and benefits of MUP.  
[normal]The experience of the provinces of Canada is most similar to the form of MUP under consideration in the UK and we would be happy to provide further briefing to the Committee if this would be helpful. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]PHE’s review of the h[bold]ealth impacts of shale gas extraction[bold]&#xa0;[bold]In relation to our discussion on the health impact of shale gas extraction there were three points the Committee wanted me to comment further on.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The first was the request to see the evidence that we co
[normal]nsidered as part of our review.  
[normal]The full list of references is set out at Annex B. 
[normal] 
[normal]We used the best available international information about the process of shale gas extraction to estimate the likely emissions from shale gas extraction, as operated in t
[normal]he context of the UK regulatory environment, and evaluate any health risks associated with those emissions.  Although shale gas extraction is itself a relatively new process, the substances involved in any emissions, and many of the industrial processes ar
[normal]e not new and their
[normal] risks are well characterised.  
[normal]For that reason we were able to draw firm conclusions about risk in relation to chemical and radiological emissions, albeit with some caveats.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Committee expressed concerns over the nature of some of t
[normal]he chemicals that may be used in shale gas extraction.  The UK will adopt a risk-based approach to the use of chemicals, and will assess the requirements for each development proposal on a site-by-site basis.  Any chemicals proposed for use in shale gas ex
[normal]traction fluid need not only to be publically disclosed, but will also be risk assessed prior to use by the Environment Agency, with subsequent peer review by the joint agencies groundwater directive advisory group (which includes PHE).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I would also like 
[normal]to provide further information on the origin and governance of the report. 
[normal] 
[normal]Our predecessor, the Health Protection Agency (HPA), initiated the review in early 2012 in response to requests for advice on the potential health impacts of shale gas extraction f
[normal]rom a wide range of stakeholders including Local Authorities, 
[normal]Directors of Public Health, NHS bodies and members of the public.  The HPA proposal for a review, and its proposed scope, was endorsed by a range of UK public health bodie
[normal]s and environmental reg
[normal]ulators.  
[normal]On 
[normal] 
[normal]1 April 2013 PHE took on the functions of the HPA.  PHE agreed the review should continue, and that PHE would publish the results.  Any other decision would have called into question the ability of our scientists to contribute to publi
[normal]c debate on the basis of the evidence.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We consider the findings of our review to be valid and robust within the scope of the draft report, and note that they are consistent with the conclusions reached in a recent Royal Society report into hydraulic fract
[normal]uring (see link 
[normal]http://royalsociety.org/policy/projects/shal
[normal]e
[normal]-gas-extracti
[normal]o
[normal]n/report
[normal]).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]PHE Workforce[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The committee requested additional information on the detaile
[normal]d breakdo
[normal]wn of PHE’s workforce.  
[normal]These are set out in Annexes C &amp; D. 
[normal]We employ a wide range of scientific, technical, professional and medical staff, on an equal
[normal]ly diverse range of activities.  
[normal]These range from specialised roles in reference laboratories, high 
[normal]containment facilities, pathology testing for the NHS and vaccine production to the delivery of screening programmes and public health support to
[normal] Local Authorities and the NHS.  
[normal]We would be happy to provide further details of our activities and their impac
[normal]t. 
[normal]I hope this further informati
[normal]on is of help to the committee.  
[normal]We stand ready to provide any further material you may find helpful.  I would like to thank the Committee for the opportunity to talk to you about what PHE does, and look forward to continui
[normal]ng our conversation.
